1 R Setup and Required Packages

In this project, the open-source R programming language (R Core Team, 2022) is used to study the U.S. Violent Causes of Death Mortality by Race/Ethnicity and Socioeconomic Factors. R is maintained by an international team of developers who make the language available at The Comprehensive R Archive Network. Readers interested in reusing our code and reproducing our results should have R installed locally on their machines. R can be installed on a number of different operating systems (see Windows, Mac, and Linux for the installation instructions for these systems). We also recommend using the RStudio interface for R. The reader can download RStudio for free by following the instructions at the link. For non-R users, we recommend the Hands-on Programming with R for a brief overview of the software’s functionality. Hereafter, we assume that the reader has an introductory understanding of the R programming language.

The snippet below documents the list of R packages and functions that were used in this study. For convenience, we used the pacman package since it allows for installing/loading the needed packages in one step.

if(require(pacman)==FALSE) install.packages("pacman") # Install pacman (if not already installed)

# Handling conflicting function names from packages

2.1 Loading the NVDRS Datasets

nvdrs_s <- read_csv("../Miljkovic_491/Miljkovic_491_nvdrs_2020_suicide.csv")
nvdrs <- read_csv("../Miljkovic_491/Miljkovic_491_nvdrs_2020.csv")


There are two NVDRS datasets provided by the Center for Disease Control and Prevention: nvdrs_2020_suicide and nvdrs_2020. The data set nvdrs_2020_suicide contains 306540 observations of 141 variables. It records all incidents from year 2003 to 2020 with suicide or intentional self-harm as manner of death. The data set nvdrs_2020 contains 193271 observations of 141 variables. It records all incidents from year 2003 to 2020 with other manner of death besides suicide or intentional self-harm.

Note:Hawaii was excluded from data year 2017, 2018, and 2020 due to incomplete case reporting. New York was excluded from data year 2019 due to incomplete case reporting. For 2016 and 2017 data, three states (Illinois, Pennsylvania, Washington) aimed to collect data on violent deaths in a subset of counties that represent at least 80% of the violent deaths in their state for that years. For 2018 data, Washington went statewide but Illinois and Pennsylvania continued to only collect data in a subset of counties representing at least 80% of violent deaths in the state that year. Because less than 100% of violent deaths were targeted for data collection, data from these states may not be fully representative of all violent deaths occurring in their states for these given years. Additionally, California collected data for violent deaths that occurred in 4 counties in 2017 (n=1,866; representing 27.8% of violent deaths that occurred in California in 2017), 21 counties in 2018 (n=3,659; representing 55.1% of violent deaths that occurred in California in 2018), 30 counties in 2019 (n=3,645; representing 55.3% of violent deaths that occurred in California in 2019), and 35 counties in 2020 (n=4,675; representing 68.1% of violent deaths that occurred in California in 2020) in accordance with requirements under which the state was funded. Texas collected data for violent deaths that occurred in 4 counties in 2020 (n=2,741; representing 40.5% of all violent deaths that occurred in Texas in 2020), in accordance with requirements under which the state was funded.

We explore these two datasets individually.

NVDRS data

  • Basic description and missing value distribution
plot_intro(nvdrs, title = "Basic Information for NVDRS Data")

We found that there were only a few deaths in some categories and decided to regroup these categories. We included counts in Terrorism homicide to Homicide and counts in Unintentional firearm - inflicted by other person and Unintentional firearm - unknown who inflicted to Unintentional firearm - other.

nvdrs$AbstractorDeathmanner_c <- recode(nvdrs$AbstractorDeathmanner_c,
                                "Terrorism homicide" = "Homicide",
                                "Unintentional firearm - inflicted by other person" = "Unintentional firearm - other", 
                                "Unintentional firearm - unknown who inflicted" = "Unintentional firearm - other")

One should note that counts in each manner of death in different years are not comparable since data in some states are not available.

missing_states <- setdiff(state.name, nvdrs$SiteID)

3 Mortality Rate Calculation

First, we create a new variable that has several age groups. One should note that there is one variable, AgeUnit, that provides the unit of age. Thus, it is important to have a consistent unit for the variable Age before analyzing the data. The table below shows the frequency distribution of the age groups in the data set nvdrs_2020 (all years).

nvdrs$Age <- ifelse(nvdrs$Age=="Unknown", "8888", nvdrs$Age)
nvdrs$Age <- as.numeric(nvdrs$Age)

nvdrs$Age <- ifelse(nvdrs$AgeUnit=="Days", nvdrs$Age/365, nvdrs$Age)

nvdrs$Age <- ifelse(nvdrs$AgeUnit=="Hours", nvdrs$Age/(365*24), nvdrs$Age)

nvdrs$Age <- ifelse(nvdrs$AgeUnit=="Minutes", nvdrs$Age/(365*24*60), nvdrs$Age)

nvdrs$Age <- ifelse(nvdrs$AgeUnit=="Weeks", nvdrs$Age*7/365, nvdrs$Age)

nvdrs <- nvdrs %>% mutate(AgeBIN = case_when(
   Age == 8888 ~ "Unknown",
   Age < 10 ~ "9-",
  (Age > 9) & (Age < 15) ~ "10-14",
  (Age > 14) & (Age < 20) ~ "15-19",
  (Age > 19) & (Age < 25) ~ "20-24",
  (Age > 24) & (Age < 30) ~ "25-29",
  (Age > 29) & (Age < 35) ~ "30-34",
  (Age > 34) & (Age < 45) ~ "35-44",
  (Age > 44) & (Age < 55) ~ "45-54",
  (Age > 54) & (Age < 65) ~ "55-64",
  (Age > 64) & (Age < 75) ~ "65-74",
  (Age > 74) & (Age < 85) ~ "75-84",
   (Age > 84) & (Age!=8888) ~ "85+"
))

#nvdrs$AgeBIN <- factor(nvdrs$AgeBIN, labels = c( "9-", "10-14", "15-19", "20-24", "25-29", "30-34", "35-44", "45-54", "55-64", "65-74","75-84", "85+", "Unknown"))

Age_Dist <- count(nvdrs, AgeBIN)
datatable(Age_Dist, colnames = c("Age", "Number of Victims"),

      initComplete = JS(

In order to use the population data downloaded from CDC Wonder, we regrouped some categories in the variable RaceEthnicity_c. The categories Unknown race, non-Hispanic, Other/Unspecified, non-Hispanic, and Two or more races, non-Hispanic” are coded to be Other.

nvdrs$RaceEthnicity_c <- recode(nvdrs$RaceEthnicity_c,
"American Indian/Alaska Native, non-Hispanic" = "American Indian or Alaska Native",
"Asian/Pacific Islander, non-Hispanic" = "Asian or Pacific Islander",
"Black or African American, non-Hispanic" = "Black or African American",
"White, non-Hispanic" = "White",
"Unknown race, non-Hispanic" = "Other",
"Other/Unspecified, non-Hispanic" = "Other",
"Two or more races, non-Hispanic" = "Other")

year19 <- nvdrs %>% filter(IncidentYear==2019)
sex_age_H <- year19 %>% filter(AbstractorDeathmanner_c=="Homicide") %>% 
  group_by(Sex, AgeBIN) %>% summarise(NoVict=n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  complete(Sex, AgeBIN, fill=list(NoVict=0))

Male_age_H <- sex_age_H %>% filter(Sex=="Male") %>% 
  mutate(Population = Pop2019_age_male$Male,

3.1 Age-Adjusted Mortality Rate - Direct Age Standardization

The current convention to calculate the age-adjusted mortality rates is to use the 2000 U.S. Standard Population. Due to the lack of data from some states and the inconsistent data available years, we calculate the age-adjusted mortality rate based on the data from the following 16 states: North Carolina, New Mexico, Kentucky, Virginia, Oklahoma, Oregon, New Jersey, Massachusetts, Wisconsin, Georgia, Utah, Rhode Island, Maryland, Colorado, South Carolina, Alaska. The data of these 16 states are available from 2005 to 2020. Thus, we will use the 2000 year population from these 16 states to calculate the age-adjusted mortality rates.

In this section, we will focus on the age-adjusted mortality rates based on direct age standardization.

In the following code chunk, we include 2000 year population from these 16 states by Sex and Age Group.

ByAge2000 <- read_tsv("../Miljkovic_491/ByAge2000.txt")
ByAge2000 <- ByAge2000 %>% select(Gender, Year, `Ten-Year Age Groups`, Population, `Crude Rate`)
ByAge2000 <- ByAge2000 %>% filter(!(`Ten-Year Age Groups` %in% c("< 1 year", "1-4 years", "Not Stated")))
